explanation: To determine whether OS_QueueDelete can lead to out-of-bounds accesses from use of <string.h> functions you must inspect the called code and the data structures/buffer sizes it manipulates. The three direct callees (OS_ObjectIdGetById, OS_QueueDelete_Impl, OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete) are required because they perform the actual lookup, delete, and finalize operations and may call string functions or copy names/payloads. Their direct callees (transaction/init/finish/cancel, conversion and index helpers, and OS_NotifyEvent) are required because those routines implement the bookkeeping and notification steps where buffer copies/formatting (memcpy/strcpy/strlen/etc.) commonly occur. The token and id type definitions (OS_object_token_t, osal_id_t), the LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE selector, and the OS_SUCCESS/return-code constants are needed to understand control flow, the content and layout of the token (pointers vs. inline buffers), and whether particular code paths that perform string operations are taken. The object table/array symbols and the name/event buffer size macros are required to determine the allocated sizes for any destination buffers that might be written by string.h functions. Finally the UT_Stub_... functions are included only if the unit-test stub instrumentation is present in the build, since those stubs can also perform buffered copies/assignments that must be checked. Inspecting the listed symbols and their implementations (and the associated size macros/structures) is sufficient to trace any uses of standard string functions and verify they cannot access beyond object bounds.
